-- Bond funds worldwide attract $3.3 bln over week - BofA
-- By Sam Forgione
-- Fri Apr 25, 2014 09:34AM EDT
-- None



NEW YORK, April 25 (Reuters) - Fund investors worldwide poured $3.3 billion into bond funds in the week ended April 23, marking the seventh straight week of inflows into the funds, data from a Bank of America Merrill Lynch Global Research report showed on Friday.

High-yield bond funds attracted $1 billion in new cash, marking 11 straight weeks of inflows into the funds. Emerging market bond funds attracted $200 million, marking their fourth straight week inflows, according to the report, which also cited data from fund-tracker EPFR Global.  Floating-rate loan funds posted $200 million in outflows, the first time since June 2012 it has seen an outflow for two straight weeks  Stock funds attracted $2.9 billion, marking their fourth straight week of inflows. Funds that specialize in U.S. stocks posted outflows, however, of $500 million. The outflows were all via mutual funds and marked the second straight week of outflows.